text: with two contests behind them the
candidates are back to debating hobbled
by a big loss in New Hampshire Hillary
Clinton tried to hone her argument for
why she's actually running for president
I'm running for president to knock down
all the barriers that are holding
Americans back and to rebuild the
ladders of opportunity that will give
every American a chance to advance
especially those who have been left out
and left behind senator Sanders tried to
show he has national appeal beyond the
very white states of Iowa and New
Hampshire and that he can be a uniter we
are fighting for every vote that we can
get from women from men straight gay
African Americans Latinos Asian
Americans we are trying to bring America
together around an agenda that works for
working families in the middle class and
he reminded African American voters a
key constituency that mrs. Clinton will
be banking on that he too feels their
pain today a male African American baby
born today stands a 1 in 4 chance of
ending up in jail that is beyond
unspeakable mrs. Clinton still the
front-runner is clearly frustrated that
her opponent is not getting more
scrutiny for his proposals which she's
described as unworkable and it's really
important now that we are getting into
the rest of the country that both of us
are held to account for explaining what
we are proposing then it is absolutely
fair and necessary for Americans to vet
both of our proposals and there were
some fiery exchanges mainly about
foreign policy so count me in is
somebody who will not be listening to
Henry Kissinger
well I know journalists have asked who
you do listen to on foreign policy and
we have yet to know who that is after
three weeks of intense campaigning in
Iowa and New Hampshire this was a
lower-energy affair there were no
knockout blows Hillary Clinton still
looks more presidential than her
opponent but he is still better at
channeling the anger and frustration of
young voters round two of this race
kicks off next week
Kim hottas BBC News in Milwaukee
Wisconsin
